@szha 
I have reverted the tag to 0.12.1 in the two places mentioned. Does this look ok now?
However I think this build script 'build_all_version.sh' is only for local testing it does not actually need the listed tag to be available on github.

@toofun666 Thanks a lot for take the time to make this PR
I will trust you here. I dont speak any Turkish, so if not white spaces is more used in the financial style, we should go this way. If later any one will need to add the option for the whites spaces they could add a PR.
I have notices several method declarations commented, could you clean up this and remove not used and commented code?

@lukesneeringer After chatting with @jonparrott it seems there is another option here.

If we could guarantee that `self._request_queue.empty()` is `True`, then we could just send `STOP` into the queue and wait until the `STOP` gets consumed, then we don't have to swap the queue.

(As you can see from the coverage failure, the queue will always be empty.)

You would have to make a method like this:
```
questionText(number) {
      return this.$tr('question', { number });
}
```
Where question is:
```
'Question Number { number }'
```

This block is duplicated in this method and the nexxt:
```
        if (this.isSuperuser) {
 +          return false;
 +        } else if (this.isAdmin) {
 +          return true;
```

Doesn't mean it needs to be de-duplicated, but may hint at a more basic concept behind the idea that 
superusers cannot edit their name/username; admins can (and for learners it depends).

@DeNeutoy I agree we should add a hash.  The old script's random number [was broken](https://github.com/allenai/allennlp/pull/757/files#diff-91c872fd064a4d494d631616c1eee34fL17) so I skipped this in my last PR (I wondered if I were missing something).

It's easy to tell whether the working tree is clean or dirty.  This is [how I handled it](https://github.com/allenai/allennlp/pull/83/files#diff-8dd2caa4ff5cd68e3b52d78173f5cc7aR28) in a PR from way back when.  However, I (and I suspect our users) often run Beaker experiments in dirty git trees.  I worry this feature would be annoying, and I want to make sure this command isn't annoying so people actually use it.

I'm uncertain about a few parts of this script.  I'm considering splitting it into two--one which builds images and one which runs images.

I'm thinking something like . . . ?
```python
if not is_bytes(address) or len(address) != 20:
    return False
return address == to_canonical_address(address)

@elyezer I disagree about this being 'personal taste'. I understand that

> nargs is a valid feature that even argparse offers

but in terms of usability, having too many values, specially if they're not associated with an argument, can lead to confusion and poor user experience imho.

I think this code can be simplified to:

```py
try:
    dns_response = dns.resolver.query(validation_domain_name, 'TXT')
except dns.exception.DNSException as error:
    logger.error(...)
    return False

for rdata in dns_response:
    for txt_record in rdata.strings:
        if txt_record == validation:
            return True
```

The logic just looks a little weird. what about

```scala
val biasUse = if (withBias) {
   ...
} else {
   null
}
```
So people will know it's a null instead of guessing what the bias is.

I'd prefer:
```python
def regularize_layer_params(layer_or_layers, penalty, ...):
    try:
        params = sum(layer.get_params(**tags) for layer in layer_or_layers, [])
    except TypeError:
        params = layer_or_layers.get_params(**tags)
    return apply_penalty(params, penalty, **kwargs)
```

@ericl what about adding a line like

```python
if registry is None:
    registry = get_registry()
```

inside the `__init__` function. Would that address the issue?
